solution: ```class Solution {
    public boolean canVisitAllRooms(List<List<Integer>> rooms) {
        int n = rooms.size();
        boolean[] seen = new boolean[n];
        java.util.Deque<Integer> stack = new java.util.ArrayDeque<>();
        stack.push(0);
        seen[0] = true;
        int count = 1;

        while (!stack.isEmpty()) {
            int room = stack.pop();
            for (int key : rooms.get(room)) {
                if (!seen[key]) {
                    seen[key] = true;
                    count++;
                    stack.push(key);
                }
            }
        }
        return count == n;
    }
}```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(N + K) where N is the number of rooms and K is the total number of keys
space complexity: O(N)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses iterative DFS with an explicit stack to avoid recursion overhead. Marks each room once, ensuring every room and key is processed exactly once.

